00:03:59.770 --> 00:04:03.280
forms a compound
nucleus, some sort

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:07.660
of large excited nucleus
that lasts for about 10

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:10.660
to the minus 14 seconds.

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:12.580
So it doesn't
instantly fizz apart.

00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:14.950
There's actually a
neutron absorption event,

00:04:14.950 --> 00:04:19.910
some sort of nuclear
instability, at which point

00:04:19.910 --> 00:04:21.709
your two fission
products break off.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.800
Notice, you don't have-- let's
call them fission product one

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:30.320
and fission product two.

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:33.500
Notice, you don't quite
have any neutrons yet.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:37.010
Neutron production is not
instantaneous for the following

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:39.290
reason.

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:42.620
If you remember back to nuclear
stability, when we plotted,

00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:47.090
let's say, I think that
was maybe Z and this was N.

00:04:47.090 --> 00:04:49.130
And I think this was
a homework problem.

00:04:49.130 --> 00:04:51.380
And you had to come up
with some sort of curve

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:56.960
of best fit for the most
stable combination of NZ

00:04:56.960 --> 00:04:57.590
for a nucleus.

00:04:57.590 --> 00:04:59.300
It was not a straight line.

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:03.670
It was something on the
order of like N equals--

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:04.350
what is it?

00:05:04.350 --> 00:05:10.840
--1.0055Z plus some constant,
something with a rather small

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:12.240
slope.

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:17.910
Well, if you have a heavy
nucleus, like uranium-235,

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:20.670
and you split it apart
evenly, let's just

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:23.310
pretend it splits
evenly for now,

00:05:23.310 --> 00:05:25.830
you're kind of
splitting that nucleus

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:28.450
along a rather unstable line.

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:31.530
And, as you saw in the
semi-empirical mass formula,

00:05:31.530 --> 00:05:34.260
a little bit of instability
goes a really long way

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:37.240
towards making the nucleus
extremely unstable.

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:41.280
So let's say you'd make a
couple of fission products

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:43.920
that just cleaved that nucleus
with the same proportion

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:45.900
of protons and neutrons.

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:47.100
How would they decay?

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:48.317
Or how can they decay?

00:05:48.317 --> 00:05:49.650
There's a couple different ways.

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:51.236
What do you guys think?

00:05:51.236 --> 00:05:53.150
AUDIENCE: It can emit neutrons.

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:55.650
MICHAEL SHORT: It
can emit neutrons

00:05:55.650 --> 00:05:58.255
if it's really
unstable, at which point

00:05:58.255 --> 00:05:59.880
it would just go down
a neutron number.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:02.632
Or how else could it decay?

00:06:02.632 --> 00:06:03.980
AUDIENCE: Alpha decay.

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:05.280
MICHAEL SHORT: Alpha decay.

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:07.220
Let's see, yeah, a
lot of those will--

00:06:07.220 --> 00:06:09.020
the heavier ones tend
to do alpha decay.

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:10.670
What would it do at alpha decay?

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:14.457
For alpha, I guess it will be
going that direction, right?

00:06:14.457 --> 00:06:15.040
You know what?

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:16.498
I'm not going to
rule that out yet.

00:06:16.498 --> 00:06:17.860
So let's go with that.

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:19.147
How else could they decay?

00:06:19.147 --> 00:06:20.570
AUDIENCE: Through beta decay.

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:21.310
MICHAEL SHORT:
Through beta decay,

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:22.855
let's say in that direction.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:27.940
Pretty much all
these happen, just

00:06:27.940 --> 00:06:29.890
not necessarily in this order.

00:06:29.890 --> 00:06:33.340
When you have a really,
really asymmetric nucleus,

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:36.450
a lot of these
fission products will

00:06:36.450 --> 00:06:40.280
emit neutrons almost
instantaneously

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:43.610
in the realm of like 10
to the minus 17 seconds,

00:06:43.610 --> 00:06:46.390
some incredibly short timeline.

00:06:46.390 --> 00:06:50.188
You will start to decay
downwards a little bit.

00:06:50.188 --> 00:06:51.730
But you're not quite
at the stability

00:06:51.730 --> 00:06:56.980
line, which is why a lot of the
fission products then go on.

00:06:56.980 --> 00:06:59.020
And they deposit
their kinetic energy

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:01.480
by bouncing around the
different atoms in material

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:02.650
creating heat.

00:07:02.650 --> 00:07:08.340
But a lot of them will also
send off betas or gammas.

00:07:13.130 --> 00:07:16.880
And it may take 10 to the
minus 13 seconds for them

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:20.150
to whatever the half-life of
that particular isotope is.

00:07:20.150 --> 00:07:24.740
And after around, let's say,
10 to the minus 10 to 10

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:27.230
to the minus 6
seconds, depending

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:31.610
on the isotope in the medium,
those two fission products

00:07:31.610 --> 00:07:32.210
will stop.

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:37.866
And let's just say
that they stop there.

00:07:37.866 --> 00:07:40.030
So the whole process of
fission, it's actually

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:41.890
quite a compound process.

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:45.940
First, the neutron is absorbed,
forming a compound nucleus.

00:07:45.940 --> 00:07:47.290
Then it splits apart.

00:07:47.290 --> 00:07:48.940
Then those individual
fission products

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:51.400
undergo whatever
decays suit them best.

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:54.250
And that's the source of
the neutrons in fission.

00:07:54.250 --> 00:07:55.960
Sometimes one of
those fission products

00:07:55.960 --> 00:07:58.000
might be particularly unstable.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.100
And it might send
off two neutrons.

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:01.930
In other cases, though
I don't know of one

00:08:01.930 --> 00:08:03.850
off the top my head,
it might be none.

00:08:03.850 --> 00:08:06.550
