00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:00.180
is because it's full of water.

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:03.480
Water, as we saw in our
old q equation argument,

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:06.120
is very good at
stopping neutrons,

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:08.130
because, if you
guys remember this,

00:12:08.130 --> 00:12:12.480
the maximum change in energy
that a neutron can get

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:16.750
is related to alpha times
its incoming energy.

00:12:16.750 --> 00:12:24.250
Or this alpha is just A minus
1 over A plus 1 squared.

00:12:24.250 --> 00:12:29.050
And I think this would actually
be a 1 minus right there.

00:12:29.050 --> 00:12:31.580
A is that mass
number of whatever

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:34.230
the neutrons are hitting.

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:37.140
And that one comes directly
from the neutron mass number.

00:12:42.090 --> 00:12:45.270
If you remember, this was
the simplest reduction

00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:48.090
of the q equation,
the generalized q

00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:50.377
equation for kinematics
that we looked at.

00:12:50.377 --> 00:12:51.960
When I said let's
do the general form,

00:12:51.960 --> 00:12:53.850
then OK, let's take
the simplest form,

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:55.560
neutron elastic scattering.

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:57.480
Here's where it comes back.

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:01.650
If a neutron hits water, which
is made mostly of hydrogen,

00:13:01.650 --> 00:13:07.230
and A is 1, then it can transfer
a maximum of all of its energy,

00:13:07.230 --> 00:13:09.477
let's say, to that
hydrogen atom, therefore,

00:13:09.477 --> 00:13:12.060
giving the neutron no energy and
thermalizing it or slowing it

00:13:12.060 --> 00:13:14.940
down very quickly.

00:13:14.940 --> 00:13:17.580
To show you what one of these
things actually looks like,

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:19.818
that's the underside of a BWR.

00:13:19.818 --> 00:13:21.360
Did [INAUDIBLE] show
you this before?

00:13:21.360 --> 00:13:21.860
OK.

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:25.022
So you've already seen what
