what it was all about.

00:15:07.420 --> 00:15:09.270
And so every single
reaction that

00:15:09.270 --> 00:15:14.610
goes on in a nuclear reactor
has got its own cross section.

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:19.400
We'll probably need half
the board for this one.

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:25.740
You can say you have a total
microscopic cross section.

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:29.070
These are all going to be as
a function of neutron energy.

00:15:29.070 --> 00:15:31.740
What's the probability of
anything happening at all?

00:15:31.740 --> 00:15:36.300
And these are actually tabulated
up on the JANIS website.

00:15:36.300 --> 00:15:39.930
So let's unclick that, get
rid of neutron production,

00:15:39.930 --> 00:15:44.260
and go all the way to
the top, n comma total.

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:47.020
So all this stuff is written
in nuclear reaction parlance,

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:50.500
where if you have, let's
say, n comma total, that

00:15:50.500 --> 00:15:55.320
means a neutron comes in, and
that's the reaction that you're

00:15:55.320 --> 00:15:57.530
looking at.

00:15:57.530 --> 00:16:01.160
So this data file here,
once I open it up,

00:16:01.160 --> 00:16:03.560
will give you the probability
that anything at all

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:05.790
will happen.

00:16:05.790 --> 00:16:08.920
You can see as the neutron
energy gets higher,

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:11.070
the probability of
anything happening at all

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:12.900
gets less, and less, and less.

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:15.750
And it follows the shape of most
of the other cross sections.

00:16:15.750 --> 00:16:17.910
And I'm going to leave
this up right there.

00:16:17.910 --> 00:16:21.150
You've also got a few
different kinds of reactions.

00:16:21.150 --> 00:16:24.710
You can have a scatter.

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:29.060
Let's call that scatter,
which we've already said

00:16:29.060 --> 00:16:31.520
can either be
elastic or inelastic.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:39.830
It may not matter
to us from the point

00:16:39.830 --> 00:16:43.610
of view of neutron physics
whether the collision

00:16:43.610 --> 00:16:46.770
is elastic or inelastic.

00:16:46.770 --> 00:16:48.720
All that matters is
the neutron goes in,

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:50.760
and a slower neutron comes out.

00:16:50.760 --> 00:16:53.460
Because what we're really
concerned with here

00:16:53.460 --> 00:16:57.330
is tracking the full
population of neutrons

00:16:57.330 --> 00:16:59.760
at any point in the reactor.

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:01.470
So we'll give this
a position vector

00:17:01.470 --> 00:17:07.380
r, which has just
got x, y, and z in it

00:17:07.380 --> 00:17:10.710
or whatever other coordinate
system you might happen to use.

00:17:10.710 --> 00:17:13.710
I prefer Cartesian,
because it makes sense.

00:17:13.710 --> 00:17:17.800
At every energy going
in any direction,

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:20.700
so we now have a
solid angled vector

00:17:20.700 --> 00:17:26.187
that's got both theta and
phi in it any given time.

00:17:26.187 --> 00:17:28.520
And the whole goal of what
we're going to be doing today

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:30.410
and all of next
week is to find out,

00:17:30.410 --> 00:17:33.110
how do you solve
for and simplify

00:17:33.110 --> 00:17:34.610
this population of neutrons?

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:42.970
Make sure to fill
that in as velocity.

00:17:51.430 --> 00:17:52.370
Let's see.

00:17:52.370 --> 00:17:55.300
Let me get back to the
cross sections and stuff.

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:57.400
If we want to know
how many neutrons

00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:03.940
are in a certain little volume
element, in some d volume,

00:18:03.940 --> 00:18:07.330
in some certain little
increment of energy, dE,

00:18:07.330 --> 00:18:11.250
traveling in some very
small, solid angle,

00:18:11.250 --> 00:18:14.170
d omega, supposedly, if
you have this function,

00:18:14.170 --> 00:18:16.810
then you know the
direction, and location,

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:18.280
and speed of every
single neutron

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:20.110
everywhere in the reactor.

00:18:20.110 --> 00:18:22.460
And this is eventually what
the goal of things like Ben

00:18:22.460 --> 00:18:24.820
and Kord's group does, the
Computational Reactor Physics

00:18:24.820 --> 00:18:28.287
Group, is solve for this or
a simplified version of it,

00:18:28.287 --> 00:18:30.370
over, and over, and over
again for different sorts

00:18:30.370 --> 00:18:31.780
of geometries.

00:18:31.780 --> 00:18:36.100
And in order to do so, you need
to know the rates of reactions

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:37.960
of every kind of
possible reaction

00:18:37.960 --> 00:18:40.995
that could take a neutron
out of its current position,

00:18:40.995 --> 00:18:43.120
like if it happens to be
moving, which most of them

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:46.390
are, out of its
current energy group.

00:18:46.390 --> 00:18:49.420
Which pretty much any reaction
will cause the neutron

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:50.920
to lose energy.

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:52.570
What's the only
reaction we've talked

00:18:52.570 --> 00:18:55.210
about where the neutron
loses absolutely no energy?

00:19:00.930 --> 00:19:02.567
It's a type of scattering.

00:19:02.567 --> 00:19:04.030
AUDIENCE: Forward scattering?

00:19:04.030 --> 00:19:06.660
MICHAEL SHORT: Yep,
exactly, forward scattering.

00:19:06.660 --> 00:19:08.790
So for forward
scattering for that case

00:19:08.790 --> 00:19:11.730
where theta scattering equals 0.

00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:15.243
Again, you missed.

00:19:15.243 --> 00:19:17.410
The neutron didn't actually
change direction at all.

00:19:17.410 --> 00:19:19.940
And, therefore, it didn't
transfer any energy.

00:19:19.940 --> 00:19:23.350
But for everything else, for
every other possible reaction,

00:19:23.350 --> 00:19:25.990
there's going to be an energy
change associated with it

00:19:25.990 --> 00:19:28.960
and probably some
corresponding change in angle,

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:30.970
because a neutron can't
just be moving, and hit

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:34.210
something, and continue
moving more slowly.

00:19:34.210 --> 00:19:38.050
There's got to be some change
in momentum to balance along

00:19:38.050 --> 00:19:40.020
with that change of energy.

00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:42.840
And it might slightly move
in some different direction.

00:19:42.840 --> 00:19:45.780
And all this is happening
as a function of time.

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:48.417
As you can see, this gets
pretty hairy pretty quick.

00:19:48.417 --> 00:19:50.250
That's why we put the
full equation for this

00:19:50.250 --> 00:19:51.877
on our department t-shirts.

00:19:51.877 --> 00:19:53.460
But no one ever
solves the full thing.

00:19:53.460 --> 00:19:55.050
What we're going to
be going over is,

00:19:55.050 --> 00:19:56.610
how do you simplify
it into something

00:19:56.610 --> 00:19:59.340
you can solve with a pen
and paper or possibly

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:00.930
a gigantic computer?

00:20:00.930 --> 00:20:03.670
But it's not impossible.

00:20:03.670 --> 00:20:05.890
So inside this sigma
total, we talked

00:20:05.890 --> 00:20:07.570
about different scattering.

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:15.310
And then you could
have absorption in

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:17.860
all its different forms.

00:20:17.860 --> 00:20:20.330
What sort of reactions
with a neutron

00:20:20.330 --> 00:20:21.580
would cause it to be absorbed?

00:20:27.036 --> 00:20:27.980
AUDIENCE: Fission.

00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:29.580
MICHAEL SHORT: Yes, fission.

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:31.130
Thank you.

00:20:31.130 --> 00:20:34.370
So there's going to be some
sigma fission cross section

00:20:34.370 --> 00:20:35.450
as a function of energy.

00:20:38.130 --> 00:20:42.260
And if it doesn't fizz,
but it is absorbed,

00:20:42.260 --> 00:20:43.260
we'll call that capture.

00:20:49.320 --> 00:20:51.750
But capture can mean a whole
bunch of different things

00:20:51.750 --> 00:20:52.505
too, right?

00:20:52.505 --> 00:20:53.880
There could be
also a whole bunch

00:20:53.880 --> 00:20:56.280
of other nuclear reactions.

00:20:56.280 --> 00:21:00.940
There could be a reaction
where one neutron comes in,

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:05.500
two neutrons go out, like
we looked at with beryllium

00:21:05.500 --> 00:21:07.930
in the Chadwick paper
from the first day

00:21:07.930 --> 00:21:13.260
or like what actually
does exist for this stuff.

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:15.790
So JANIS doesn't
like multi-touch,

00:21:15.790 --> 00:21:19.870
so you have to bear with me on
the small print on the screen.

00:21:19.870 --> 00:21:21.715
But there should
be-- yep, here it is.

00:21:21.715 --> 00:21:25.480
Cross section number 16,
there is a probability

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:26.980
that one neutron goes in.

00:21:26.980 --> 00:21:31.060
That z right there is whatever
your incoming particle

00:21:31.060 --> 00:21:31.870
happens to be.

00:21:31.870 --> 00:21:34.180
And in this case, we know
it's a neutron, because we

00:21:34.180 --> 00:21:35.940
picked incident neutron data.

00:21:35.940 --> 00:21:38.920
And 2n means two
neutrons come out.

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:42.090
Let's plot that cross section.

00:21:42.090 --> 00:21:46.890
You can see that the value is
0 until you hit about 4 or 5.

00:21:46.890 --> 00:21:52.290
Oh, it's actually 5.297781 MeV.

00:21:52.290 --> 00:21:54.960
So that's the q value at
which this particular reaction

00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:57.130
happens to turn on.

00:21:57.130 --> 00:22:00.370
Might be responsible for
a little bit of the blip

00:22:00.370 --> 00:22:02.200
in the total cross section.

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:05.185
So technically, if we were
to turn on every single cross

00:22:05.185 --> 00:22:09.580
section in this database, it
should add up to that red line

00:22:09.580 --> 00:22:11.260
right there.

00:22:11.260 --> 00:22:14.500
So you can start to get an
idea for how much of all

00:22:14.500 --> 00:22:17.770
the reactions of uranium-235
are due to fission.

00:22:17.770 --> 00:22:20.550
That's the one we
want to exploit.

00:22:20.550 --> 00:22:24.690
So let's find fission,
right down there.

00:22:24.690 --> 00:22:26.420
Oh, wow, there's a 3n reaction.

00:22:26.420 --> 00:22:28.670
I want to see that.

00:22:28.670 --> 00:22:32.240
That doesn't happen
until 12 MeV.

00:22:32.240 --> 00:22:32.940
Yeah.

00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:35.700
So neutrons don't
typically tend to hit

00:22:35.700 --> 00:22:38.880
12 MeV in a fission reactor.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:41.400
So this is a perfect
flimsy pretext

00:22:41.400 --> 00:22:43.470
to bring in another variable.

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:48.140
It's called the chi spectrum or
what's called the fission birth

00:22:48.140 --> 00:22:48.640
spectrum.

00:22:54.702 --> 00:22:55.202
Yeah.

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:01.490
We've already talked about
the neutrons being born

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:02.990
and how many there were.

00:23:02.990 --> 00:23:06.410
But we didn't say at
what energy they're born.

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:11.590
In fusion reactors,
this is pretty simple.

00:23:11.590 --> 00:23:14.040
You've already
looked at this case.

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:14.540
What is it?

00:23:14.540 --> 00:23:16.790
14.7 MeV.

00:23:16.790 --> 00:23:18.500
That's a lot simpler.

00:23:18.500 --> 00:23:20.810
That's the fusion.

00:23:20.810 --> 00:23:22.820
For fission, it's not so simple.

00:23:25.340 --> 00:23:29.450
For the case of fission, if
you draw energy versus this chi

00:23:29.450 --> 00:23:35.890
spectrum, it takes an
interesting looking curve

00:23:35.890 --> 00:23:42.590
from about 1 MeV to about 10
MeV with the most likely energy

00:23:42.590 --> 00:23:44.930
being around 2 MeV.

00:23:44.930 --> 00:23:48.050
So you aren't really
going to get neutrons

00:23:48.050 --> 00:23:52.040
at the energy required for a 3n
reaction in a regular fission

00:23:52.040 --> 00:23:54.790
reactor, just not
going to happen.

00:23:54.790 --> 00:23:57.140
But it's good that you
know that that exists.

00:23:57.140 --> 00:23:59.310
So let's go and answer
my original question.

00:23:59.310 --> 00:24:01.850
How much of the total cross
section is due to fission?

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:10.850
Most of it, especially
at low energies.

00:24:10.850 --> 00:24:12.890
So let me get rid of
those 2n and 3n ones,

00:24:12.890 --> 00:24:16.110
because they're kind
of ruining our data.

00:24:16.110 --> 00:24:17.500
It's making it harder to see.

00:24:23.810 --> 00:24:25.730
That's better.

00:24:25.730 --> 00:24:30.860
So you can see at energies below
around, let's say, a keV or so,

00:24:30.860 --> 00:24:33.650
almost all of the reactions
happening with neutrons

00:24:33.650 --> 00:24:35.720
in uranium-235 are fission.

00:24:35.720 --> 00:24:37.970
This is part of what makes
it such a particularly good

00:24:37.970 --> 00:24:39.980
isotope to use in reactors.

00:24:39.980 --> 00:24:42.560
The other one is, you can
find it in the ground,

00:24:42.560 --> 00:24:46.440
unlike most of the other
fissile isotopes, unlike,

00:24:46.440 --> 00:24:49.020
I think, any of the
other fissile isotopes.

00:24:49.020 --> 00:24:52.450
Thorium you got to breed and
turn it into uranium-233.

00:24:52.450 --> 00:24:55.002
I'll have to think
about that one.

00:24:55.002 --> 00:24:56.460
But then you start
to look at, what

00:24:56.460 --> 00:24:59.190
are the other components
of this cross section,

00:24:59.190 --> 00:25:03.600
like zn prime, inelastic
scattering, which

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:09.600
doesn't turn on until
about 0.002 MeV,

00:25:09.600 --> 00:25:12.180
but later on is one of
the major contributors

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:13.810
and actually is
responsible for--

00:25:13.810 --> 00:25:15.750
wait, I've brought
this for a reason.

00:25:15.750 --> 00:25:18.855
--is responsible for that
little bump in the total cross

00:25:18.855 --> 00:25:19.710
section.

00:25:19.710 --> 00:25:22.740
So eventually all
these things do matter.

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:25.520
But let's think about which
ones we actually care about

00:25:25.520 --> 00:25:30.080
at all, because what we
eventually want to do

00:25:30.080 --> 00:25:34.850
is develop some sort of
neutron balance equation.

00:25:34.850 --> 00:25:37.310
If we can measure the change
in the number of neutrons

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:45.140
as a function of position,
energy, angle, and time,

00:25:45.140 --> 00:25:47.720
as a function of time,
and that would probably

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:50.780
be a partial derivative, because
there are like seven variables

00:25:50.780 --> 00:25:52.550
here.

00:25:52.550 --> 00:25:54.270
Before I write any
equations, it's

00:25:54.270 --> 00:25:56.645
just going to be a measure of
the gains minus the losses.

00:26:00.070 --> 00:26:02.840
And while every particular
reaction has its own cross

00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:06.610
section, there's only going to
