00:28:06.150 --> 00:28:08.400
So onto some gas cooled
reactors and to explain

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:09.780
some of these acronyms.

00:28:09.780 --> 00:28:13.133
There are some that use natural
uranium, though pretty much all

00:28:13.133 --> 00:28:14.550
the ones in this
country, you need

00:28:14.550 --> 00:28:16.590
to enrich the
uranium to get enough

00:28:16.590 --> 00:28:19.350
U-235 to turn the reaction on.

00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:22.890
But you don't have to
do that in every case.

00:28:22.890 --> 00:28:26.550
And you'll also see these
acronyms, LEU, MEU, or HEU,

00:28:26.550 --> 00:28:30.420
standing for Low, Medium,
or High Enrichment.

00:28:30.420 --> 00:28:33.240
The accepted standard for
what's low enriched uranium

00:28:33.240 --> 00:28:35.780
is 20% or below.

00:28:35.780 --> 00:28:37.470
An interesting fact,
though, you can't

00:28:37.470 --> 00:28:42.930
have something at
19.99% enriched uranium

00:28:42.930 --> 00:28:45.245
and expect it to be
low enriched uranium,

00:28:45.245 --> 00:28:47.370
because every measurement
technique has some error.

00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:48.787
And what really
determines if it's

00:28:48.787 --> 00:28:51.870
LEU is when an inspector
comes and takes a sample,

00:28:51.870 --> 00:28:55.620
it better be below 20%
including their error.

00:28:55.620 --> 00:29:00.570
So you'll usually see 19.75%
given as the LEU limit,

00:29:00.570 --> 00:29:02.850
because there's always
some processing error,

00:29:02.850 --> 00:29:05.160
inhomogeneities,
measurement error.

00:29:05.160 --> 00:29:07.950
Hedge your bets, pretty much.

00:29:07.950 --> 00:29:10.770
Like in England or the UK,
the advanced gas reactors

00:29:10.770 --> 00:29:13.110
have been churning
along for decades.

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:16.090
They actually use
CO2 as the coolant,

00:29:16.090 --> 00:29:18.000
which is relatively inert.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.240
And they use graphite
as the moderator.

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:22.740
So in this case, the coolant
and the moderator are separate,

00:29:22.740 --> 00:29:25.230
unlike the light water
reactors we have.

00:29:25.230 --> 00:29:28.920
So this way, the graphite, right
here, just sits in solid form

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:31.890
and slows down the neutrons,
not quite as good as water,

00:29:31.890 --> 00:29:33.210
but pretty good.

00:29:33.210 --> 00:29:38.100
There is an issue, though, that
CO2, just like anything, has

00:29:38.100 --> 00:29:44.410
a natural decomposition
reaction, where CO2 naturally

00:29:44.410 --> 00:29:49.390
is in equilibrium
with CO and O2.

00:29:49.390 --> 00:29:55.090
And O2 plus graphite
yields CO2 gas.

00:29:55.090 --> 00:29:57.647
Graphite was solid.

00:29:57.647 --> 00:29:59.980
In talking with a couple folks
from the National Nuclear

00:29:59.980 --> 00:30:02.470
Laboratory, they said
that 40 years later, when

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:05.110
they took the caps
off these reactors,

00:30:05.110 --> 00:30:10.410
a lot of that graphite was just
gone with a good explanation.

00:30:10.410 --> 00:30:15.360
It vaporized very, very, very
slowly over 40 years or so due

00:30:15.360 --> 00:30:19.650
to this natural recombination
with whatever little bit of O2

00:30:19.650 --> 00:30:22.820
is in equilibrium with CO2
and possibly some other leaks.

00:30:22.820 --> 00:30:25.320
I'm sure I wouldn't have been
told that if there was a leak.

00:30:25.320 --> 00:30:27.510
So I'd say the
feasibility is high,

00:30:27.510 --> 00:30:30.300
because they've been running
for almost half a century.

00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:32.722
The power density is very low.

00:30:32.722 --> 00:30:34.305
Why do you guys think
that's the case?

00:30:37.548 --> 00:30:38.534
Yeah.

00:30:38.534 --> 00:30:43.464
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:43.464 --> 00:30:44.450
MICHAEL SHORT: Mm-hm.

00:30:44.450 --> 00:30:47.057
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:47.057 --> 00:30:48.140
MICHAEL SHORT: Absolutely.

00:30:48.140 --> 00:30:50.920
So well, let's say, you need
the same cooling capacity,

00:30:50.920 --> 00:30:51.870
but you're right.

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:55.230
CO2, even if pressurized, is not
as good a heat transfer medium

00:30:55.230 --> 00:30:55.730
as water.

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:57.200
Water is dense.

00:30:57.200 --> 00:30:59.700
It's also got one of the highest
heat capacities of anything

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:01.050
we've ever seen.

00:31:01.050 --> 00:31:04.020
The other reason is right here.

00:31:04.020 --> 00:31:05.655
If you want enough
reaction density,

00:31:05.655 --> 00:31:09.240
then it not only matters
what the per atom density is,

00:31:09.240 --> 00:31:12.150
but what the number density is.

00:31:12.150 --> 00:31:14.490
And if you're using
gaseous CO2 coolant,

00:31:14.490 --> 00:31:17.310
even if it's pressurized,
there are fewer reactions

00:31:17.310 --> 00:31:19.440
happening per unit
volume, because there

00:31:19.440 --> 00:31:23.880
are few CO2 molecules per unit
volume than water would have.

00:31:23.880 --> 00:31:27.060
So that's why we pressurize
our light water reactors,

00:31:27.060 --> 00:31:28.560
to keep water in
its liquid state

00:31:28.560 --> 00:31:31.440
where it's a great heat
absorber, takes a lot of energy

00:31:31.440 --> 00:31:33.180
to boil it, and
it's really dense

00:31:33.180 --> 00:31:37.524
so it's a very effective
dense moderator.

00:31:37.524 --> 00:31:38.925
These have been around forever.

00:31:38.925 --> 00:31:39.540
Let me think.

00:31:39.540 --> 00:31:42.000
When did Windscale happen?

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:45.870
Windscale was also the
source of an interesting fire

00:31:45.870 --> 00:31:47.560
that you guys might
want to know about.

00:31:47.560 --> 00:31:50.010
It's one of those
only nuclear disasters

00:31:50.010 --> 00:31:53.190
that hit 7 on the
arbitrary unit scale.

00:31:53.190 --> 00:31:56.010
I don't quite know how they
determine what's a seven.

00:31:56.010 --> 00:31:58.380
But there was a fire
at the Windscale plant

00:31:58.380 --> 00:32:01.750
due to the build up of
what's called Wigner energy.

00:32:01.750 --> 00:32:04.380
It turns out that when
neutrons go slamming around

00:32:04.380 --> 00:32:08.580
in the graphite, they leave
behind radiation damage.

00:32:08.580 --> 00:32:11.340
And when my family always
asks me to explain,

00:32:11.340 --> 00:32:12.540
what do you do for a living?

00:32:12.540 --> 00:32:15.780
And I can only think, well, they
don't know radiation damage.

00:32:15.780 --> 00:32:17.340
They've watched Harry Potter.

00:32:17.340 --> 00:32:20.760
I'd like to say, radiation,
like dark magic, leaves traces.

00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:22.380
Well, it leaves
traces in the graphite

00:32:22.380 --> 00:32:27.150
in the form of atomic defects,
which took energy to create.

00:32:27.150 --> 00:32:29.820
So by causing damage
to the graphite,

00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:32.850
you store energy in it, which
is known as Wigner energy.

00:32:32.850 --> 00:32:35.730
And you can store so
much that it just catches

00:32:35.730 --> 00:32:37.770
fire and explodes sometimes.

00:32:37.770 --> 00:32:40.080
That's what happened
here at Windscale.

00:32:40.080 --> 00:32:42.397
11 tons of uranium
ended up burning,

00:32:42.397 --> 00:32:44.730
because all of a sudden, the
temperature in the graphite

00:32:44.730 --> 00:32:47.280
just started going up
for no reason, no reason

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:48.842
that they understood
at the time.

00:32:48.842 --> 00:32:51.300
It turns out that they had
built up enough radiation damage

00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:54.480
energy that it started
releasing more heat.

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:57.240
And releasing more heat
caused more of that energy

00:32:57.240 --> 00:33:00.240
to be released, and it
was self-perpetuating

00:33:00.240 --> 00:33:03.930
until it just caught fire and
burned 11 tons of uranium out

00:33:03.930 --> 00:33:04.810
in the countryside.

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:06.900
This was 1957.

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:12.900
So again, a 7 on the scale with
no units of nuclear disasters.

00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:15.090
Argue it's probably not
as bad as Chernobyl,

00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:19.900
so they might want a little bit
of resolution in that scale.

00:33:19.900 --> 00:33:22.840
There's another type of gas cool
reactor called the Pebble Bed

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:25.720
Modular Reactor, a much more
up and coming one, where

00:33:25.720 --> 00:33:28.570
each fuel element-- you
don't have fuel rods.

00:33:28.570 --> 00:33:30.370
You've actually
got little pebbles

00:33:30.370 --> 00:33:32.570
full of tiny kernels of fuel.

00:33:32.570 --> 00:33:34.630
So you've got a built-in
graphite moderator

00:33:34.630 --> 00:33:38.110
tennis ball sized thing with
lots of little grains of sand

00:33:38.110 --> 00:33:41.920
of UO2 cooled by
a bed of flowing

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:44.050
helium or something like that.

00:33:44.050 --> 00:33:46.420
And then that helium,
or the other gas,

00:33:46.420 --> 00:33:49.660
transfers heat to water,
which goes in to make steam

00:33:49.660 --> 00:33:53.514
and goes into the turbine
like I showed you before.

00:33:53.514 --> 00:33:55.940
So this is what the fuel
actually looks like.

00:33:55.940 --> 00:33:58.190
Inside each one of
these tennis ball

00:33:58.190 --> 00:34:00.650
spheres of mostly
graphite, there's

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:02.870
these little kernels
of uranium dioxide

00:34:02.870 --> 00:34:05.540
about a half a
millimeter across covered

00:34:05.540 --> 00:34:08.420
in layers of silicon
carbide, a really strong

00:34:08.420 --> 00:34:11.920
and dense material that keeps
the fission products in,

00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:14.790
because the biggest
danger from nuclear fuel

00:34:14.790 --> 00:34:18.510
is the highly radioactive
fission products that

00:34:18.510 --> 00:34:20.429
due to their instability
are giving off

00:34:20.429 --> 00:34:24.060
all sorts of awful, for
anywhere from milliseconds

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:27.747
to mega years, after
reactor operation.

00:34:27.747 --> 00:34:29.580
And so if you keep those
out of the coolant,

00:34:29.580 --> 00:34:32.489
then the coolant stays
relatively nonradioactive.

00:34:32.489 --> 00:34:36.962
And it's safe to do things
like maintain the plant.

00:34:36.962 --> 00:34:38.920
Then there's the very
high temperature reactor,

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:41.500
the ultimate in
acronym creativity.

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:43.850
It operates at a very
high temperature,

00:34:43.850 --> 00:34:46.150
which has been
steadily decreasing

00:34:46.150 --> 00:34:50.440
over time, as reality has
caught up to expectations.

00:34:50.440 --> 00:34:52.630
When I first got into this
field, they were saying,

00:34:52.630 --> 00:34:55.272
we're going to run
this at 1100 Celsius.

00:34:55.272 --> 00:34:56.980
Then I started studying
material science.

00:34:56.980 --> 00:35:00.250
And I was like, yeah, nothing
wants to be 1100 Celsius.

00:35:00.250 --> 00:35:02.650
By that time, they
downgraded it to 1000.

00:35:02.650 --> 00:35:06.040
Now they've asymptoted
it at around 800 or 850

00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:10.570
due to some actual problems
in operating things in helium.

00:35:10.570 --> 00:35:13.070
It's not the helium itself, but
the impurities in the helium

00:35:13.070 --> 00:35:14.915
that could really mess you up.

00:35:14.915 --> 00:35:16.290
And the sorts of
alloys that they

00:35:16.290 --> 00:35:19.890
need to get this working,
these nickel superalloys,

00:35:19.890 --> 00:35:22.440
like Alloy 230,
they can slightly

00:35:22.440 --> 00:35:24.510
carburize or
decarburize depending

00:35:24.510 --> 00:35:26.760
on the amount of carbon
in the helium coolant.

00:35:26.760 --> 00:35:31.230
Either way you go, you lose
the strength that you need.

00:35:31.230 --> 00:35:33.100
So I'll say feasibility
is low to medium,

00:35:33.100 --> 00:35:37.122
because, well, we haven't
really seen one of these yet.

00:35:37.122 --> 00:35:38.455
Then onto water cooled reactors.

00:35:38.455 --> 00:35:40.240
Has anyone here
heard of the reactors

00:35:40.240 --> 00:35:43.340
they have in Canada,
the CANDU reactors?

00:35:43.340 --> 00:35:44.740
That's my favorite acronym.

00:35:44.740 --> 00:35:46.760
I hope that was intentional.

00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:47.260
It what?

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:48.220
AUDIENCE: It's convenient.

00:35:48.220 --> 00:35:49.053
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

00:35:49.053 --> 00:35:51.100
[LAUGHS] It's not like the--

00:35:51.100 --> 00:35:54.100
well, they're not sorry
about anything, but whatever.

00:35:54.100 --> 00:35:56.800
At any rate, one of the
nice features about this

00:35:56.800 --> 00:36:00.640
is you can actually use natural
uranium, because the moderator

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:02.063
is heavy water.

00:36:02.063 --> 00:36:04.480
You have to look into what the
sort of cross sections are.

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:09.490
Even though deuterium
won't slow down neutrons

00:36:09.490 --> 00:36:12.220
as much as hydrogen will--
where did my alpha thing-- oh,

00:36:12.220 --> 00:36:13.850
it was right here all along.

00:36:13.850 --> 00:36:17.070
Even though A is 2 instead
of 1 for deuterium,

00:36:17.070 --> 00:36:19.990
it's absorption cross section,
or specifically-- yeah,

00:36:19.990 --> 00:36:21.320
because it doesn't fission.

00:36:21.320 --> 00:36:26.257
Its absorption cross section is
way lower than that of water.

00:36:26.257 --> 00:36:28.090
It actually functions
as a better moderator,

00:36:28.090 --> 00:36:31.570
because fewer of those
collisions are absorption.

00:36:31.570 --> 00:36:34.150
And because you have a better
neutron population and less

00:36:34.150 --> 00:36:36.880
absorption, you don't need
to enrich your uranium.

00:36:36.880 --> 00:36:39.770
You also don't need to
pressurize your moderator.

00:36:39.770 --> 00:36:43.000
So you can flow some other
coolant through these pressure

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:46.810
tubes and just have a big tank
of close to something room

00:36:46.810 --> 00:36:50.460
temperature unpressurized
D2O as your moderator.

00:36:50.460 --> 00:36:55.300
The problem with that
is D2O is expensive.

00:36:55.300 --> 00:36:59.415
Anyone priced out
deuterium oxide before?

00:36:59.415 --> 00:37:01.040
Probably have at the
reactor, because I

00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:03.619
know you have drums of it.

00:37:03.619 --> 00:37:07.323
AUDIENCE: It's like a couple
thousand per kilogram.

00:37:07.323 --> 00:37:08.990
MICHAEL SHORT: A
couple thousand a kilo,

00:37:08.990 --> 00:37:10.910
it's an expensive
bottle of water.

00:37:10.910 --> 00:37:14.260
It'll also mess you up if you
drink it, because a lot of it,

00:37:14.260 --> 00:37:16.150
even if it's crystal
clear, filtered

00:37:16.150 --> 00:37:19.690
D2O, a lot of what the
cellular machinery depends

00:37:19.690 --> 00:37:23.350
on the diffusion coefficients
of various things in water,

00:37:23.350 --> 00:37:25.540
those solutes in water.

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:27.820
And if you change the
mass of the water,

00:37:27.820 --> 00:37:30.320
then the diffusion coefficients
of the water itself,

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:32.400
as well as the things
in it, will change.

00:37:32.400 --> 00:37:35.200
And if you depend on, let's
say, exact sodium and potassium

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:37.330
concentrations for your
nerves to function,

00:37:37.330 --> 00:37:39.310
a little change in
that can go a long way

00:37:39.310 --> 00:37:42.170
towards giving you a bad day.

00:37:42.170 --> 00:37:44.030
And actually, we have
a little piece of one

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:47.100
of these pressure tubes upstairs
if anyone wants to take a look.

00:37:47.100 --> 00:37:49.100
There's all these
sealed fuel bundles

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:51.770
inside what they call
a calandria tube,

00:37:51.770 --> 00:37:54.590
just a pressurized
tube that's horizontal.

00:37:54.590 --> 00:37:56.390
The problem with
some of these is

00:37:56.390 --> 00:37:58.730
if these spacers get
knocked out of place, which

00:37:58.730 --> 00:38:00.650
they do all the
time, those tubes

00:38:00.650 --> 00:38:03.050
can start to creep
downward and get

00:38:03.050 --> 00:38:06.830
a little harder to cool or touch
the sides and change thermal.

00:38:06.830 --> 00:38:09.240
And now I'm getting
into material science.

00:38:09.240 --> 00:38:11.320
It's a mess.

00:38:11.320 --> 00:38:16.000
Then there's the old RBMK, the
reactor that caused Chernobyl.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:20.230
You can also use natural uranium
or low enriched uranium here.

00:38:20.230 --> 00:38:22.660
The problem though that
led to Chernobyl-- one

00:38:22.660 --> 00:38:25.450
of the many problems that
led to Chernobyl was,

00:38:25.450 --> 00:38:27.380
you've got all this
moderator right here.

00:38:27.380 --> 00:38:30.340
So if you lose your coolant,
let's say you had a light water

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:33.580
reactor and your coolant goes
away, your moderator also

00:38:33.580 --> 00:38:38.140
goes away, which means your
neutrons don't slow down

00:38:38.140 --> 00:38:39.190
anymore.

00:38:39.190 --> 00:38:41.680
That one reaction is messing up.

00:38:41.680 --> 00:38:42.580
There we go.

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:45.140
Which means your neutrons
don't slow down anymore,

00:38:45.140 --> 00:38:47.140
which means the probability
of fission happening

00:38:47.140 --> 00:38:50.320
could be like
10,000 times lower.

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:52.858
So losing coolant in
a light water reactor,

00:38:52.858 --> 00:38:54.650
temperature might go
up, but it's not going

00:38:54.650 --> 00:38:56.690
to give you a nuclear bad day.

00:38:56.690 --> 00:39:00.340
In the RBMK reactor,
it will and it did.

00:39:00.340 --> 00:39:02.860
And in addition,
the control rods,

00:39:02.860 --> 00:39:05.950
which were supposed to shut down
the reaction, made of things

00:39:05.950 --> 00:39:08.590
like boron 4 carbide,
or hafnium, or something

00:39:08.590 --> 00:39:12.390
with a really high
capture cross section

00:39:12.390 --> 00:39:15.150
were tipped with graphite
to help them ease in.

00:39:15.150 --> 00:39:17.760
So you've got
moderator tipped rods,

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:20.490
which induce additional
moderation, which

00:39:20.490 --> 00:39:23.790
helps slow down the
neutrons even more to where

00:39:23.790 --> 00:39:25.087
they fission even better.

00:39:25.087 --> 00:39:27.420
And that's what led to what's
called a positive feedback

00:39:27.420 --> 00:39:28.560
coefficient.

00:39:28.560 --> 00:39:30.670
So the more you tried to
insert the control rods

00:39:30.670 --> 00:39:32.212
and the more you
tried to fix things,

00:39:32.212 --> 00:39:34.680
the worse things got
in the nuclear sense.

00:39:34.680 --> 00:39:37.320
And in something like
a quarter of a second,

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:40.470
the reactor power went
up by like 35,000 times.

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:43.350
And we'll do a millisecond by
millisecond rundown of what

00:39:43.350 --> 00:39:46.467
happened in Chernobyl after
we do all this neutron

00:39:46.467 --> 00:39:48.300
physics stuff when
you'll be better equipped

00:39:48.300 --> 00:39:49.050
to understand it.

00:39:49.050 --> 00:39:52.620
But suffice to say, there were
some positive coefficients here

00:39:52.620 --> 00:39:55.890
that are to be avoided at all
costs in all nuclear reactor

00:39:55.890 --> 00:39:58.410
design.

00:39:58.410 --> 00:40:00.480
In the actual reactor
hall you can go and stand

00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:01.560
on one of these things.

00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:04.020
It's a very different design
from what you're used to.

00:40:04.020 --> 00:40:05.687
I don't think anyone
would let you stand

00:40:05.687 --> 00:40:06.912
on top of a pressure vessel.

00:40:06.912 --> 00:40:09.120
First, your shoes would
melt, because they're usually

00:40:09.120 --> 00:40:11.418
at like 300 Celsius or so.

00:40:11.418 --> 00:40:13.710
And second of all, you'd
probably get a little too much

00:40:13.710 --> 00:40:14.790
radiation.

00:40:14.790 --> 00:40:17.190
But this is actually
what an RBMK reactor

00:40:17.190 --> 00:40:21.200
hall looks like for one of
the units that didn't blow up.

00:40:21.200 --> 00:40:23.970
There were multiple
units at that site.

00:40:23.970 --> 00:40:26.370
Then there's the
supercritical water reactor.

00:40:26.370 --> 00:40:28.830
Let's say you want to run
at higher temperatures

00:40:28.830 --> 00:40:31.200
than regular water
will allow you to.

00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:34.290
You can pressurize
it so much that water

00:40:34.290 --> 00:40:37.800
goes beyond the supercritical
point in the phase sense

00:40:37.800 --> 00:40:41.700
and starts to behave not
like liquid, not like a gas,

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:44.400
but somewhere in between,
something that's really, really

00:40:44.400 --> 00:40:47.610
dense, so getting towards
the density of water, not

00:40:47.610 --> 00:40:50.130
quite, which means it's
still a great moderator,

00:40:50.130 --> 00:40:52.410
but still can cool the
materials quite well

00:40:52.410 --> 00:40:56.130
to extract heat to make
power and so on and so on.

00:40:56.130 --> 00:40:56.810
Yeah.

00:40:56.810 --> 00:40:59.260
AUDIENCE: So supercritical
refers to the coolant

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:01.720
not the neutrons?

00:41:01.720 --> 00:41:03.310
MICHAEL SHORT: Good question.

00:41:03.310 --> 00:41:05.030
For a supercritical
water reactor,

00:41:05.030 --> 00:41:07.780
it most definitely
refers to the coolant.

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:09.295
It's the phase of
the coolant where

00:41:09.295 --> 00:41:13.270
it's beyond the liquid
gas separation line,

00:41:13.270 --> 00:41:15.220
and it's just
something in between.

00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:17.920
Any of these reactors
can go supercritical,

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:20.680
where you're producing more
neutrons than you're consuming.

00:41:20.680 --> 00:41:23.110
And that is a nuclear bad day.

00:41:23.110 --> 00:41:24.760
But the supercritical
water reactor

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:28.480
does not refer to neutron
population, just a coolant.

00:41:28.480 --> 00:41:29.797
Good question.

00:41:29.797 --> 00:41:30.880
It's never come up before.

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:34.630
But it's like, should
have thought of that.

00:41:34.630 --> 00:41:37.360
And so then my favorite,
liquid metal reactors,

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:40.750
like LBE, or
Lead-Bismuth Eutectic.

00:41:40.750 --> 00:41:44.080
It's a low melting point
alloy of lead and bismuth.

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:48.803
Lead melts at around 330
Celsius, bismuth 200 something.

00:41:48.803 --> 00:41:51.220
Put them together, and it's
like a low temperature solder.

00:41:51.220 --> 00:41:54.190
It melts at 123.5 Celsius.

00:41:54.190 --> 00:41:56.078
You can melt it in a frying pan.

00:41:56.078 --> 00:41:58.120
This is nice, because you
don't want your coolant

00:41:58.120 --> 00:42:01.460
to freeze when you're
trying to cool your reactor,

00:42:01.460 --> 00:42:04.570
because imagine something
happens, you lose power.

00:42:04.570 --> 00:42:06.610
The coolant freezes
somewhere outside the core.

00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:08.740
You can't get the
core cool again.

00:42:08.740 --> 00:42:10.360
That's called a loss
of flow accident

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:12.250
that can lead to
a really bad day.

00:42:12.250 --> 00:42:14.620
And the lower your melting
point is the better.

00:42:14.620 --> 00:42:17.770
Sodium potassium is already
molten to begin with.

00:42:17.770 --> 00:42:20.030
Sodium melts at like 90 Celsius.

00:42:20.030 --> 00:42:22.000
And when you add two
different metals together,

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:24.610
you almost always
lower the melting point

00:42:24.610 --> 00:42:25.852
of the combination.

00:42:25.852 --> 00:42:27.310
In this case,
forming what's called

00:42:27.310 --> 00:42:32.540
the eutectic, or a lowest
possible melting point alloy.

00:42:32.540 --> 00:42:35.690
The sodium fast reactor
has a number of advantages,

00:42:35.690 --> 00:42:37.760
like you don't really
need any pressure.

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:40.280
As long as you have a cover
gas keeping the sodium

00:42:40.280 --> 00:42:43.940
from reacting with anything,
like the moisture in the air,

00:42:43.940 --> 00:42:45.980
or any errant water
in the room, you

00:42:45.980 --> 00:42:48.370
can just circulate
it through the core.

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:51.500
And liquid metals are
awesome heat conductors.

00:42:51.500 --> 00:42:53.900
They might not have
the best heat capacity,

00:42:53.900 --> 00:42:56.930
as in how much energy per gram
they can store like water.

00:42:56.930 --> 00:42:58.520
But they're really
good conductors

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:00.770
with very high
thermal conductivity.

00:43:00.770 --> 00:43:04.680
They also are really good at
not slowing down neutrons.

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:07.700
So these tend to be what's
called fast reactors that

00:43:07.700 --> 00:43:11.960
rely on the ability of
other isotopes of uranium,

00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:15.540
like uranium-238, to undergo
what's called fast fission.

00:43:15.540 --> 00:43:18.100
And I want to show you
what that looks like.

00:43:18.100 --> 00:43:23.325
Let's pull up U-238 and look
at its fission cross section.

00:43:23.325 --> 00:43:24.700
And you might find
that it should

00:43:24.700 --> 00:43:28.340
look a fair bit different.

00:43:28.340 --> 00:43:37.220
So we'll go down to number
18 to fission cross section,

00:43:37.220 --> 00:43:38.960
very, very different.

00:43:38.960 --> 00:43:44.940
So U-238 is pretty terrible
at fission at low energies.

00:43:44.940 --> 00:43:46.870
It's pretty good at
capturing neutrons.

00:43:46.870 --> 00:43:48.750
This is where we
get plutonium-239,

00:43:48.750 --> 00:43:50.660
like you guys saw on the exam.

00:43:50.660 --> 00:43:53.160
But then you go to really high
energies and all of a sudden,

00:43:53.160 --> 00:43:58.630
it gets pretty good at
undergoing fission on its own.

00:43:58.630 --> 00:44:00.720
And so the basis behind
a lot of fast reactors

00:44:00.720 --> 00:44:03.990
is a combination of making
their own fuel and the fact

00:44:03.990 --> 00:44:08.010
that uranium-238 fast
fissions even better than it

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:09.023
thermal fissions.

00:44:09.023 --> 00:44:10.440
So something good
for you to know,

00:44:10.440 --> 00:44:12.900
even though it's
not a fissile fuel,

00:44:12.900 --> 00:44:15.316
that's light water
reactor people talking.

00:44:15.316 --> 00:44:19.900
You can get it to fission if
the neutron populations higher.

00:44:19.900 --> 00:44:21.970
Now, there's some
problems with this.

00:44:21.970 --> 00:44:28.870
It takes some time for neutrons
to slow down from 1 to 10 MeV

00:44:28.870 --> 00:44:31.780
to about 0.025 eV.

00:44:31.780 --> 00:44:35.022
If your neutrons don't need to
slow down and travel anywhere,

00:44:35.022 --> 00:44:37.480
and pretty much all they have
to do is be born and absorbed

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:40.990
by a nearby uranium
atom, the feedback time

00:44:40.990 --> 00:44:43.210
is faster in these
sorts of reactors.

00:44:43.210 --> 00:44:45.970
They're inherently more
difficult to control.

00:44:45.970 --> 00:44:49.690
And you can't use normal
physics like thermal expansion

00:44:49.690 --> 00:44:51.740
of things that might happen
on the order of micro

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:55.810
to nanoseconds if it takes less
time than that for one neutron

00:44:55.810 --> 00:44:58.510
to be born and find
another uranium atom.

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:01.670
You can still use it somewhat,
but not quite as much.

00:45:01.670 --> 00:45:05.790
So it's something to note
backed up by nuclear data.

00:45:05.790 --> 00:45:07.790
And that's what one of
them actually looks like.

00:45:07.790 --> 00:45:09.860
These things have
been built. That's

00:45:09.860 --> 00:45:14.280
a blob of liquid sodium on
the Monju reactor in Japan.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:16.190
And where I was all
last week in Russia,

00:45:16.190 --> 00:45:18.590
they actually have
fleets of fast reactors.

00:45:18.590 --> 00:45:24.410
Their BN-300 and BN-600 reactors
are 300 and 600 megawatt sodium

00:45:24.410 --> 00:45:25.910
cooled reactors.

00:45:25.910 --> 00:45:27.560
One of them in the
Chelyabinsk region

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:29.822
they use pretty much
for desalination

00:45:29.822 --> 00:45:31.280
down in the center
of Russia, where

00:45:31.280 --> 00:45:35.180
there's no oceans nearby
and probably dirty water.

00:45:35.180 --> 00:45:38.655
They actually use that
to make clean water.

00:45:38.655 --> 00:45:40.280
They also use this
for power production

00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:42.470
and for radiation
damage studies.

00:45:42.470 --> 00:45:45.800
So when it comes to
radiation material science,

00:45:45.800 --> 00:45:49.990
these fast reactors are
really where it's at.

00:45:49.990 --> 00:45:52.920
Yeah, you just
noticed the bottom.

00:45:52.920 --> 00:45:55.290
I went to Belgium, to their
national nuclear labs,

00:45:55.290 --> 00:45:57.330
where they have a
slowing sodium test loop.

00:45:57.330 --> 00:45:59.580
It's not a reactor, but it's
like a thermal hydraulics

00:45:59.580 --> 00:46:01.430
and materials test loop.

00:46:01.430 --> 00:46:03.000
And I asked a simple question.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:04.790
Where's the bathroom?

00:46:04.790 --> 00:46:06.420
And they started laughing at me.

00:46:06.420 --> 00:46:09.370
And they said, we're not putting
any plumbing in a sodium loop

00:46:09.370 --> 00:46:10.540
building.

00:46:10.540 --> 00:46:12.373
You'll have to go to
the next building over.

00:46:12.373 --> 00:46:14.957
And that's when I noticed, there
weren't any sprinkler systems

00:46:14.957 --> 00:46:15.900
or toilets.

00:46:15.900 --> 00:46:19.650
But every 15 or 20 feet, there
was a giant barrel of sand.

00:46:19.650 --> 00:46:22.530
That's the fire extinguisher
for a liquid metal fire

00:46:22.530 --> 00:46:24.720
is you just cover it with
sand, absorb the heat,

00:46:24.720 --> 00:46:28.125
keep the air out, the moisture
out, wick away the moisture

00:46:28.125 --> 00:46:29.430
or whatever else sand does.

00:46:29.430 --> 00:46:30.920
I don't know.

00:46:30.920 --> 00:46:33.090
But you can't use normal
fire extinguishers

00:46:33.090 --> 00:46:34.810
to put out a sodium fire.

00:46:34.810 --> 00:46:37.765
AUDIENCE: When you said sand,
I thought of kitty litter.

00:46:37.765 --> 00:46:38.760
MICHAEL SHORT: Ah.

00:46:38.760 --> 00:46:40.093
I don't know if that would work.

00:46:40.093 --> 00:46:42.197
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:42.197 --> 00:46:43.280
I guess it's worth a shot.

00:46:43.280 --> 00:46:44.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:44.760 --> 00:46:47.460
With glasses, and safety,
and stuff, of course.

00:46:47.460 --> 00:46:49.610
And the ones that I spent
the most time working on,

00:46:49.610 --> 00:46:51.440
like I showed you in
the paper yesterday,

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:53.970
is the lead or
lead-bismuth fast reactor.

00:46:53.970 --> 00:46:56.300
This one does not
have the disadvantages

00:46:56.300 --> 00:46:57.802
of exploding like sodium.

00:46:57.802 --> 00:47:00.260
It does have the disadvantage,
like I showed you yesterday,

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:03.720
of corroding everything,
pretty much everything.

00:47:03.720 --> 00:47:07.083
And so the one thing keeping
this thing back was corrosion.

00:47:07.083 --> 00:47:08.500
And I say the
ultimate temperature

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:10.340
is medium, but higher soon.

00:47:10.340 --> 00:47:11.840
Hopefully, someone
picks up our work

00:47:11.840 --> 00:47:14.215
and is like, yeah, that was
a good idea, because we think

00:47:14.215 --> 00:47:16.340
it can raise the
outlet temperature

00:47:16.340 --> 00:47:19.180
of a lead-bismuth reactor
by like 100 Celsius

00:47:19.180 --> 00:47:21.860
as long as some other unforeseen
problem doesn't pop up,

00:47:21.860 --> 00:47:24.360
and we don't quite know yet.

00:47:24.360 --> 00:47:27.240
These things also
already exist in the form

00:47:27.240 --> 00:47:30.720
of the Alfa Class attack
submarines from the Soviet

00:47:30.720 --> 00:47:31.770
Union.

00:47:31.770 --> 00:47:34.592
These are the only subs
that can outrun a torpedo.

00:47:34.592 --> 00:47:37.550
So you know that old algebra
problem, if person A leaves

00:47:37.550 --> 00:47:39.380
Pittsburgh at 40 miles
an hour and person

00:47:39.380 --> 00:47:41.750
B leaves Boston at
30 miles an hour,

00:47:41.750 --> 00:47:45.620
where do the trains collide or
I forget how it actually ends?

00:47:45.620 --> 00:47:48.650
Well, in the end, if a
torpedo leaves an American sub

00:47:48.650 --> 00:47:52.640
at whatever speed and the Alfa
Class submarine notices it,

00:47:52.640 --> 00:47:55.700
how close do they have to be
before the torpedo runs out

00:47:55.700 --> 00:47:56.970
of gas?

00:47:56.970 --> 00:48:00.020
So what I was told by the
designer of these subs,

00:48:00.020 --> 00:48:03.463
a fellow by the name of Georgy
Toshinsky, when he came here

00:48:03.463 --> 00:48:05.630
to talk about his experience
with these lead-bismuth

00:48:05.630 --> 00:48:09.020
reactors is, there is a
button on the sub that's

00:48:09.020 --> 00:48:12.790
the Forget About Safety,
It's a Torpedo button.

00:48:12.790 --> 00:48:15.940
Because if you're underwater
in a lead-bismuth reactor

00:48:15.940 --> 00:48:17.860
and a torpedo is
heading at you, you

00:48:17.860 --> 00:48:21.730
have a choice between maybe
dying in a nuclear catastrophe

00:48:21.730 --> 00:48:24.650
and definitely dying
in a torpedo explosion.

00:48:24.650 --> 00:48:29.060
Well, that button is the
I Like Those Odds button.

00:48:29.060 --> 00:48:31.400
And you just give full
power to the engines

00:48:31.400 --> 00:48:33.590
and whatever else
happens, happens.

00:48:33.590 --> 00:48:37.340
The point is, you may be
able to outrun the torpedo.

00:48:37.340 --> 00:48:40.800
And quite popular nowadays,
especially in this department,

00:48:40.800 --> 00:48:44.070
is molten salt cooled reactors
that actually use liquid salt,

00:48:44.070 --> 00:48:47.960
not dissolved, but molten
salt itself as the coolant.

00:48:47.960 --> 00:48:50.940
It doesn't have as many of
the corrosion problems as lead

00:48:50.940 --> 00:48:53.610
or the exploding
problems as sodium.

00:48:53.610 --> 00:48:56.160
It does have a high melting
point problem though.

00:48:56.160 --> 00:48:59.340
They tend to melt at
around 450 degrees Celsius.

00:48:59.340 --> 00:49:01.110
But there's one
pretty cool feature.

00:49:01.110 --> 00:49:03.600
You can dissolve
uranium in them.

00:49:03.600 --> 00:49:05.250
So remember how in
light water reactors

00:49:05.250 --> 00:49:07.620
the coolant is
also the moderator?

00:49:07.620 --> 00:49:09.570
In molten salt
reactors, the coolant

00:49:09.570 --> 00:49:12.790
is also the fuel, because
you can have principally

00:49:12.790 --> 00:49:15.400
uranium and lithium
fluoride salt

00:49:15.400 --> 00:49:17.008
co-dissolved in each other.

00:49:17.008 --> 00:49:18.550
And the way you make
a reactor is you

00:49:18.550 --> 00:49:22.630
just flow a bunch of that
salt into nearby pipes.

00:49:22.630 --> 00:49:26.280
And then you get less, what's
called, neutron leakage,

00:49:26.280 --> 00:49:28.520
where in each of these pipes
once in a while uranium

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:29.728
will give off a few neutrons.

00:49:29.728 --> 00:49:32.228
Most of them will just come out
the other ends of the pipes,

00:49:32.228 --> 00:49:33.880
and you won't have a reaction.

00:49:33.880 --> 00:49:36.010
When you put a whole bunch
of molten salt together,

00:49:36.010 --> 00:49:38.230
